he hardest things for me, now that I''m famous, is finding people who can read my stuff and give me an honest critique.', 9110, 0), (441320, 'Once you''re famous you can''t go back.', 70726, 0), (441321, 'My mother was never very famous when I was growing up, so it wasn''t so difficult. It was only when I left home and went to university that she become this style icon.', 70727, 0), (441322, 'The hardest thing about being famous is that people are always nice to you.', 29124, 0), (441323, 'I''m the man that made wrestling famous.', 66791, 0), (441324, 'Famous old houses seem to have an intuitive perception of the value of corner lots. If it is a possible thing, they always set themselves down on the most desirable spots.', 5885, 0), (441325, 'Being in ''Us Weekly'' does not make you famous.', 66638, 0), (441326, 'I was a shy kid, but somehow I knew I would make it as a performer. I''d always be telling my mum that I was going to be a famous singer. In my school yearbooks I would write, ''Remember me when I''m famous.'' I knew I had a gift.', 25639, 0), (441327, 'The true fans were capable of not only painting their cars and homes their team colors, but also naming family pets and offspring after famous NFL all-stars.', 70728, 0), (441328, 'I''ve worked with a lot of people who are more famous than myself who are terribly insecure.', 70729, 0), (441329, 'My reaction when I hear the word ''celebrity'' is, ''Who, me?'' It doesn''t feel like I''m famous.', 70730, 0), (441330, 'Being big and famous doesn''t get you more freedom, it gets you less.', 70731, 0), (441331, 'Normal is such a hard word to use, because everyone''s idea of normal is different. Real is what the word is. I think you either live a real life or you live a weird celebrity pseudolife. I think I lead a really real life.', 70732, 0), (441332, 'The more they applaud, the bigger your salary will be.', 55096, 0), (441333, 'I felt so painfully isolated that I vowed I would get revenge on the world by becoming a famous cartoonist.', 70733, 0), (441334, 'I drive around on my scooter in Milan alone - we don''t have bodyguards or anything like that. I am a fashion designer, not a celebrity, and although I get stopped for autographs and the like, I don''t think I am famous.', 68143, 0), (441335, 'I''m coming out with a wine... I''m actually a restaurateur. I have Famous Famiglia Pizzeria that has opened up in the Sacramento airport. I''m also working with my business partner on opening up the Linnethia Lounge.', 69062, 0), (441336, 'You''re not famous until my mother has heard of you.', 9115, 0), (441337, 'I don''t see myself as a famous person.', 70734, 0), (441338, 'None of my characters are rich or famous, and the situations they find themselves in could happen to anyone.', 19, 0), (441339, 'Celebrity distorts democracy by giving the rich, beautiful, and famous more authority than they deserve.', 20538, 0), (441340, 'Celebrity is the advantage of being known to people who we don''t know, and who don''t know us.', 1011, 0), (441341, 'I don''t see myself as famous I see myself as a normal person with a job that is not very normal. My work life is very out there and very public. But I do my best to maintain my privacy. ', 70735, 0), (441342, 'You do stand-up because you have to do it. If you''re doing it to become ''famous,'' you''re wrong. If you''re doing it to become a millionaire, you''re doing it for the wrong reasons. In 2003, I was flat broke. I''d been doing stand-up for 14 years at that point. I loved it and just kept at it.', 68518, 0), (441343, 'I love going to the beach. I like just walking around South Beach, but sometimes, when you''re famous, it can be a little difficult.', 70736, 0), (441344, 'I can do whatever I want - I''m rich, I''m famous, and I''m bigger than you.', 66770, 0), (441345, 'Kids will keep it real. If I''ve ever had in my life a great anchor, it''s them. They get in your head, ''don''t get too famous.'' If you think you''re really famous and